The problem requires finding the probability that the maximum number of successes for one of the three drugs exceeds 8, given that each drug has a success probability of 0.7 and there are 10 independent triples (each triple assigns one patient to each drug).

For each drug, the number of successes follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds 8 is equivalent to \(P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) > 8)\), where \(S_i\) is the number of successes for drug \(i\).

This is calculated as \(1 - P(\max(S_1, S_2, S_3) \leq 8) = 1 - [P(S \leq 8)]^3\), since the \(S_i\) are identical and independent.

First, compute \(P(S > 8)\) for one drug:
- \(P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)

Then, \(P(S \leq 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\).

Next, compute \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = (0.8506916541)^3\):
- \((0.8506916541)^2 = 0.723676478\)
- \((0.723676478) \times 0.8506916541 = 0.615625141\)
- Thus, \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) \approx 0.615625\)

Finally, \(P(\max(S_i) > 8) = 1 - 0.615625 = 0.384375\).

Rounded to three decimal places, the probability is 0.384.

